2500|$|Although a {{particle}} hypothetically behaving {{as a point}} mass would be reflected, {{a particle}} actually behaving as a matter wave has a finite probability that it will penetrate the barrier and continue its travel as a wave on the other side. In classical wave-physics, this effect is known as <b>evanescent</b> <b>wave</b> coupling. [...] The likelihood that the particle will pass through the barrier is given by the transmission coefficient, whereas the likelihood that it is reflected is given by the reflection coefficient. [...] Schrödinger's wave-equation allows these coefficients to be calculated.|$|E
